Predicting Tumor Malignancy: A Comparative Study of Supervised Learning Models with Ensemble Techniques

Boning Liu

11-14-2024

1 Introduction

In this project, I will be exploring and applying supervised learning techniques to predict the classification of breast cancer tumors as either malignant or benign. The objective is to develop a predictive model using a dataset containing various tumor attributes, derived from medical imaging. By implementing and comparing different machine learning models, such as logistic regression and a single-layer neural network, I aim to identify which model provides the highest predictive accuracy.

Key Questions We Are Trying to Solve:

  • Can we accurately classify tumors as malignant or benign based on their physical characteristics?

  • Which machine learning model offers the best performance for this classification task?

  • What are the sensitivity and specificity of each model, and how well do they perform in terms of overall accuracy?

  • How does the performance of simpler models (e.g., logistic regression) compare to more complex models (e.g., neural networks and decision trees)?

To assess the performance of these models, I will use metrics such as accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, and the area under the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve. Additionally, I will evaluate each model’s effectiveness in distinguishing between malignant and benign tumors to determine the best-performing model. This analysis not only demonstrates practical applications of machine learning in the healthcare domain but also highlights the strengths and weaknesses of various predictive algorithms.

1.1 Data Set

For this analysis, I am using the Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) Dataset. This dataset is publicly available on Kaggle and originates from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. It includes 569 observations with 30 attributes that describe characteristics of cell nuclei present in digital images of breast masses. These characteristics are used to predict the binary outcome: Malignant (coded as 1) or Benign (coded as 0).

Key Variables in the Dataset:

  • diagnosis: Diagnosis of tumor (Malignant/Benign) - Categorical (Binary)

  • radius_mean: Mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter - Numerical

  • texture_mean: Standard deviation of gray-scale values - Numerical

  • perimeter_mean: Mean size of the tumor perimeter - Numerical

  • area_mean: Mean area of the tumor - Numerical

  • smoothness_mean: Mean of local variation in radius lengths - Numerical

  • compactness_mean: Mean of the perimeter squared divided by the area - Numerical

  • concavity_mean: Mean severity of concave portions of the contour - Numerical

  • concave points_mean: Mean number of concave portions of the contour - Numerical

  • symmetry_mean: Mean symmetry of the tumor - Numerical

  • fractal_dimension_mean: Mean “coastline approximation” of the tumor - Numerical

Additional features include “standard error” (SE) values and “worst” (largest) values for each of these characteristics, allowing for more detailed descriptions of each tumor’s features.

This dataset provides a robust set of predictors, enabling the development of a highly accurate classification model to predict whether a tumor is malignant or benign.

Diagnosis Variable:

The diagnosis variable has values of 0 and 1, corresponding to Benign (0) and Malignant (1), respectively. The data appears to be imbalanced, with more benign cases than malignant ones (based on the summary statistics showing a higher mean for 0).

Numerical Variables:

radius_mean, texture_mean, perimeter_mean, area_mean, etc.: These are the key numerical features derived from the breast mass images. The summary shows the range of values for these variables, which indicates the spread and variation across the dataset. For example, radius_mean has a range from 6.98 to 28.11, indicating variation in the tumor sizes.

radius_worst, texture_worst, area_worst, etc.: These variables represent the “worst” or largest value for each characteristic. The summary shows that these values tend to be higher than the mean or standard deviation values (e.g., radius_worst ranges from 7.93 to 49.54). Distributions:

The large differences between the mean and median for some variables, such as radius_worst (mean = 16.28, median = 14.97), suggest potential skewness in their distributions. This would be an important consideration for modeling, as skewed data can impact model performance, especially for linear models like logistic regression.

Variables like concavity_worst, compactness_worst, and fractal_dimension_worst show some higher values in the max category, indicating potential outliers or extreme values.

2.2 Analysis of Target Variable Distribution

library(ggplot2)

# Bar plot for target variable 'diagnosis'
ggplot(breast_cancer_data, aes(x = factor(diagnosis))) +
  geom_bar(fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Diagnosis", x = "Diagnosis (0 = Benign, 1 = Malignant)", y = "Count")

The bar plot above shows the distribution of the target variable, diagnosis, which indicates whether a breast tumor is benign (0) or malignant (1). From the plot, it is evident that:

  • There are more benign cases than malignant cases in this dataset.

  • The count of benign tumors (coded as 0) is significantly higher than the count of malignant tumors (coded as 1). Specifically, we observe that approximately two-thirds of the cases are benign, while one-third are malignant.

This imbalance in the target variable is important to consider, as it may affect model performance. Models trained on imbalanced data may be biased toward the majority class (benign in this case), leading to higher accuracy for benign predictions but potentially lower accuracy for malignant predictions. To address this, we may need to explore methods such as adjusting class weights or using techniques like resampling or synthetic data generation in future modeling steps.

The histograms above illustrate the distributions of two important predictor variables, Radius Mean and Texture Mean, in the dataset.

  1. Radius Mean:

  • The radius_mean variable, which represents the average distance from the center of the tumor to points on its perimeter, shows a right-skewed distribution. The majority of values are concentrated between 10 and 15, with a few cases extending up to around 25.

  • This skewness suggests that a larger number of tumors have smaller radius values, with fewer cases having large radii. The presence of some high values might indicate potential outliers or tumors with significantly larger radii.

  1. Texture Mean:

  • The texture_mean variable, representing the standard deviation of gray-scale values in the tumor images, has a distribution closer to normal, though it is slightly right-skewed. Most values fall between 15 and 25, with a peak around 20.

  • This relatively normal distribution suggests a more balanced spread of texture values across the dataset. The range, however, still extends from below 10 to nearly 40, indicating a moderate level of variability.

These distributions are important to consider for modeling, as skewed variables may affect model assumptions and performance, particularly in linear models. Transformations, such as logarithmic or square root transformations, might be considered to normalize these distributions if needed. However, since many machine learning models can handle non-normal distributions, this may not be necessary unless issues are observed during model evaluation.

3 Part I

3.1 Logistic Regression

# Split data into training and testing sets
set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility
trainIndex <- sample(seq_len(nrow(breast_cancer_data)), size = 0.8 * nrow(breast_cancer_data))
training_data <- breast_cancer_data[trainIndex, ]
testing_data <- breast_cancer_data[-trainIndex, ]

# Logistic Regression Model
logistic_model <- glm(diagnosis ~ ., data = training_data, family = "binomial")

# Predict on test set
logistic_predictions <- predict(logistic_model, testing_data, type = "response")
logistic_predicted_classes <- ifelse(logistic_predictions > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Evaluate logistic regression model
logistic_conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(factor(logistic_predicted_classes), 
                                        factor(testing_data$diagnosis))
print(logistic_conf_matrix)

The logistic regression model was used to predict whether a breast tumor is benign (0) or malignant (1) based on various features. Below is an interpretation of the results:

  1. Confusion Matrix:

  • The confusion matrix shows the model’s predictions compared to the actual classifications:

    • True Negatives (Benign predicted as Benign): 58

    • False Positives (Malignant predicted as Benign): 0

    • False Negatives (Benign predicted as Malignant): 3

    • True Positives (Malignant predicted as Malignant): 53

  1. Model Performance Metrics:

  • Accuracy: The model achieved an accuracy of 97.37%, indicating that it correctly predicted the tumor classification in approximately 97.4% of the cases.

  • Sensitivity (True Positive Rate): 95.08%, meaning the model correctly identified 95.08% of benign tumors.

  • Specificity (True Negative Rate): 100%, meaning the model correctly identified all malignant tumors without any false positives.

  • Positive Predictive Value (Precision): 100%, indicating that all tumors predicted as benign were indeed benign.

  • Negative Predictive Value: 94.64%, meaning that 94.64% of tumors predicted as malignant were truly malignant.

  1. ROC Curve and AUC:

  • The ROC curve for this model shows a strong separation between the two classes, with the curve hugging the top-left corner of the plot. This suggests excellent model performance.

  • The high specificity and sensitivity values contribute to an area under the curve (AUC) close to 1, indicating that the model effectively distinguishes between benign and malignant tumors.

  1. Overall Model Interpretation:

  • The high accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity values indicate that the logistic regression model performs exceptionally well on this dataset, with minimal misclassifications. This performance, combined with the ROC curve, suggests that the model is highly effective at identifying both benign and malignant tumors.

  • However, the model’s perfect specificity may be partly due to class imbalance or the characteristics of this particular dataset. Testing the model on a new dataset would help determine its generalizability.

  • Given the poor performance, this model may not be suitable for predicting tumor classifications in this analysis without further optimization.

4.1 Decision Algorithm Implementation

# Load necessary libraries

# Fit a decision tree model
tree_model <- rpart(diagnosis ~ ., data = training_data, method = "class")

# Plot the decision tree for interpretation
rpart.plot(tree_model, type = 3, extra = 101, fallen.leaves = TRUE, main = "Decision Tree for Tumor Classification")

# Predict on the test set
tree_predictions <- predict(tree_model, testing_data, type = "prob")[, 2]

4.2 Model Comparison using ROC Analysis

# Plot ROC curves for all three models on the same plot for comparison

# Logistic Regression ROC curve
logistic_roc_curve <- roc(testing_data$diagnosis, logistic_predictions)
plot(logistic_roc_curve, col = "black", lwd = 2, main = "ROC Curve Comparison for All Models")

# Neural Network ROC curve

# Calculate and display AUC for each model
logistic_auc <- auc(logistic_roc_curve)

print(paste("Logistic Regression AUC:", round(logistic_auc, 3)))

To evaluate the performance of the logistic regression, neural network, and decision tree models, we compared their ROC curves and calculated their AUC (Area Under the Curve) values. A higher AUC indicates a better-performing model, as it reflects a stronger ability to distinguish between benign and malignant tumors.

  1. Logistic Regression:

  • AUC: 0.984

  • The logistic regression model performed exceptionally well, achieving the highest AUC of 0.984. Its ROC curve is close to the top-left corner, indicating excellent sensitivity and specificity.

  1. Neural Network:

  • AUC: 0.5

  • The single-layer neural network model performed poorly, with an AUC of 0.5. This AUC value suggests that the model’s performance is equivalent to random guessing, as seen by its diagonal ROC curve. This model did not effectively distinguish between the two classes in this dataset.

  1. Decision Tree:
  • AUC: 0.953

The decision tree model also performed well, achieving an AUC of 0.953. Its ROC curve is close to that of the logistic regression model, indicating strong classification performance. However, it slightly underperforms compared to logistic regression.

Conclusion

Based on the ROC analysis and AUC values, the logistic regression model is the best-performing model, with the highest AUC of 0.984. This model demonstrates the strongest ability to correctly classify benign and malignant tumors, making it the most reliable choice for this task. While the decision tree model also performed well with an AUC of 0.953, the logistic regression model provides a marginally better classification performance. The neural network model, with an AUC of 0.5, did not perform adequately in this analysis.

5 Part III

5.1 Implementing the BAGGING Algorithm

# Install and load the randomForest package if not already installed
if (!require(randomForest)) {
  install.packages("randomForest")
  library(randomForest)
} else {
  library(randomForest)
}
# Ensure all column names are syntactically valid
colnames(training_data) <- make.names(colnames(training_data))
colnames(testing_data) <- make.names(colnames(testing_data))

# Ensure diagnosis is a factor in both training and testing datasets
training_data$diagnosis <- factor(training_data$diagnosis)
testing_data$diagnosis <- factor(testing_data$diagnosis)

# Fit the Random Forest model (bagging with decision trees)
set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility
rf_model <- randomForest(diagnosis ~ ., data = training_data, ntree = 50)

# Predict probabilities on the test set
rf_predictions <- predict(rf_model, testing_data, type = "prob")[, 2]
rf_predicted_classes <- ifelse(rf_predictions > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Evaluate the Bagging model (Random Forest)
rf_conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(factor(rf_predicted_classes), factor(testing_data$diagnosis))
print(rf_conf_matrix)

  1. Confusion Matrix:

  • The confusion matrix shows the model’s predictions compared to the actual classifications:

    • True Negatives (Benign predicted as Benign): 61

    • False Positives (Malignant predicted as Benign): 2

    • False Negatives (Benign predicted as Malignant): 0

    • True Positives (Malignant predicted as Malignant): 51

  1. Model Performance Metrics:

  • Accuracy: The model achieved an accuracy of 98.25%, indicating a high level of correct classifications.

  • Sensitivity (True Positive Rate): 100%, meaning the model correctly identified all benign tumors.

  • Specificity (True Negative Rate): 96.23%, indicating that the model correctly identified 96.23% of malignant tumors.

  • Positive Predictive Value (Precision): 96.83%, showing that 96.83% of the cases predicted as benign were truly benign.

  • Negative Predictive Value: 100%, indicating that all cases predicted as malignant were indeed malignant.

  1. ROC Curve and AUC:

  • The ROC curve for the bagging model (purple) shows a strong performance with a curve close to the top-left corner, indicating excellent sensitivity and specificity.

  • The bagging model’s ROC curve closely aligns with that of the logistic regression and decision tree models, suggesting comparable or slightly improved performance.

  1. Overall Model Interpretation:

  • The bagging model performed exceptionally well, achieving high accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity. This strong performance indicates that the ensemble approach of bagging contributed to better classification accuracy and robustness.

  • Compared to the other models, the bagging model offers a slightly higher accuracy and balanced accuracy, making it a strong candidate for tumor classification tasks.

Conclusion

After comparing the ROC curves and AUC values of all models (logistic regression, neural network, decision tree, and bagging), the bagging model (random forest) demonstrated the best overall performance, with high sensitivity, specificity, and accuracy. This model is therefore recommended as the best choice for this classification task.
